<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-11-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-11-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="689" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d689">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/10647a</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-11-02">
                                        <hi rend="italic">November 2, 1916</hi>
                                    </date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4009. Your 5023, October 16, and Department’s November 1. On May 8,
                                S. S. <hi rend="italic">Nieuw Amsterdam</hi> left Rotterdam with
                                1,146 bags sugar-beet seed for Wisconsin Sugar Company. This was not
                                one of the cases brought to the attention of the Foreign Office at
                                the time of <persName corresp="#p_SJHA1">Stabler</persName>’s
                                conversation with Cadogan in February, nor was any special request
                                made by Department for shipment to Wisconsin Company, hence shipment
                                could only have been made under the general assurances given
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SJHA1">Stabler</persName>. This shows that
                                Foreign Office must have been informed of general arrangement and
                                acting thereon confirmed it, making it all the more binding in
                                character. Present this information to Foreign Office and urge
                                immediate assurances of non-interference with shipment Michigan
                                Company and <persName>DeRekowski</persName> seed now in
                                Rotterdam.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>